<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-209-078  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 209 078.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  April 1989 v40 n4 p14(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Making the transition: systems analysis to management</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferratt, Thomas W.; Starke, Frederick A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Systems analysts may consider, at some point in their careers,moving from the technical-professional (T-P) side over tomanagement.andP;  Systems analysts should understand what motivatesthem as a systems analyst and how this matches with the motivationneeded in line management.andP;  Research shows the top five motivatorsfor T-Ps are meaningful work, supportive working relationships,respect, appreciation and a clear job.andP;  The top five for managersare meaningful work, authority, influence, respect andappreciation.andP;  Systems analysts should consider three aspects of acareer transition before making the change: the analyst may not behappy doing work that requires fundamentally differentmotivations; the analyst might not be maximally productive ifmotivating factors are ignored; changes in motivations may changethe analyst's self image or relationships with others.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Career DevelopmentJob SatisfactionSelf AppraisalSystems AnalystsMotivationManagement Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Instrument for measuring motivators of productive work behavior.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>